events.description: Sack of Rome: Vandals enter Rome, and plunder the city for two weeks.
events.html: • 455 – Sack of Rome: Vandals enter Rome, and plunder the city for two weeks.[1]

events.description: First Crusade: The first Siege of Antioch ends as Crusader forces take the city; the second siege began five days later.
events.html: • 1098 – First Crusade: The first Siege of Antioch ends as Crusader forces take the city; the second siege began five days later.[2]

events.description: The Colony of Virginia gets a charter, extending borders from "sea to sea".
events.html: • 1608 – The Colony of Virginia gets a charter, extending borders from "sea to sea".[3]

events.description: The first Récollet missionaries arrive at Quebec City, from Rouen, France.
events.html: • 1615 – The first Récollet missionaries arrive at Quebec City, from Rouen, France.[4]

events.description: Franco-Dutch War: France ensured the supremacy of its naval fleet for the remainder of the war with its victory in the Battle of Palermo.
events.html: • 1676 – Franco-Dutch War: France ensured the supremacy of its naval fleet for the remainder of the war with its victory in the Battle of Palermo.[5]

events.description: Bridget Bishop is the first person to be tried for witchcraft in Salem, Massachusetts; she was found guilty the same day and hanged on June 10.
events.html: • 1692 – Bridget Bishop is the first person to be tried for witchcraft in Salem, Massachusetts; she was found guilty the same day and hanged on June 10.[6]

events.description: Pontiac's Rebellion: At what is now Mackinaw City, Michigan, Chippewas capture Fort Michilimackinac by diverting the garrison's attention with a game of lacrosse, then chasing a ball into the fort.
events.html: • 1763 – Pontiac's Rebellion: At what is now Mackinaw City, Michigan, Chippewas capture Fort Michilimackinac by diverting the garrison's attention with a game of lacrosse, then chasing a ball into the fort.[7]

events.description: Intolerable Acts: The Quartering Act of 1774 is enacted, allowing a governor in colonial America to house British soldiers in uninhabited houses, outhouses, barns, or other buildings if suitable quarters are not provided.
events.html: • 1774 – Intolerable Acts: The Quartering Act of 1774 is enacted, allowing a governor in colonial America to house British soldiers in uninhabited houses, outhouses, barns, or other buildings if suitable quarters are not provided.[8]

events.description: The anti-Catholic Gordon Riots in London leave an estimated 300 to 700 people dead.
events.html: • 1780 – The anti-Catholic Gordon Riots in London leave an estimated 300 to 700 people dead.[9]

events.description: French Revolution: François Hanriot, leader of the Parisian National Guard, arrests 22 Girondists selected by Jean-Paul Marat, setting the stage for the Reign of Terror.
events.html: • 1793 – French Revolution: François Hanriot, leader of the Parisian National Guard, arrests 22 Girondists selected by Jean-Paul Marat, setting the stage for the Reign of Terror.[10]

events.description: Napoleonic Wars: A Franco-Spanish fleet recaptures from the British the island of Diamond Rock, which guards the entrance to the bay leading to Fort-de-France, Martinique.
events.html: • 1805 – Napoleonic Wars: A Franco-Spanish fleet recaptures from the British the island of Diamond Rock, which guards the entrance to the bay leading to Fort-de-France, Martinique.[11]

events.description: The Slavic Congress opens in Prague.
events.html: • 1848 – The Slavic Congress opens in Prague.[12]

events.description: The Fenians defeat Canadian forces at Ridgeway and Fort Erie, but the raids end soon after.
events.html: • 1866 – The Fenians defeat Canadian forces at Ridgeway and Fort Erie, but the raids end soon after.

events.description: Guglielmo Marconi applies for a patent for his wireless telegraph.
events.html: • 1896 – Guglielmo Marconi applies for a patent for his wireless telegraph.

events.description: Alfred Deakin becomes Prime Minister of Australia for the third time.
events.html: • 1909 – Alfred Deakin becomes Prime Minister of Australia for the third time.

events.description: Charles Rolls, a co-founder of Rolls-Royce Limited, becomes the first man to make a non-stop double crossing of the English Channel by plane.
events.html: • 1910 – Charles Rolls, a co-founder of Rolls-Royce Limited, becomes the first man to make a non-stop double crossing of the English Channel by plane.

events.description: Anarchists simultaneously set off bombs in eight separate U.S. cities.
events.html: • 1919 – Anarchists simultaneously set off bombs in eight separate U.S. cities.

events.description: U.S. President Calvin Coolidge signs the Indian Citizenship Act into law, granting citizenship to all Native Americans born within the territorial limits of the United States.
events.html: • 1924 – U.S. President Calvin Coolidge signs the Indian Citizenship Act into law, granting citizenship to all Native Americans born within the territorial limits of the United States.

entities.name: Native Americans in the United States

events.description: World War II: German paratroopers murder Greek civilians in the villages of Kondomari and Alikianos.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: German paratroopers murder Greek civilians in the villages of Kondomari and Alikianos.

events.description: Birth of the Italian Republic: In a referendum, Italians vote to turn Italy from a monarchy into a Republic. After the referendum, King Umberto II of Italy is exiled.
events.html: • 1946 – Birth of the Italian Republic: In a referendum, Italians vote to turn Italy from a monarchy into a Republic. After the referendum, King Umberto II of Italy is exiled.

events.description: The coronation of Queen Elizabeth II at Westminster Abbey becomes the first British coronation and one of the first major international events to be televised.
events.html: • 1953 – The coronation of Queen Elizabeth II at Westminster Abbey becomes the first British coronation[13] and one of the first major international events to be televised.[14]

events.description: The USSR and Yugoslavia sign the Belgrade declaration and thus normalize relations between the two countries, discontinued since 1948.
events.html: • 1955 – The USSR and Yugoslavia sign the Belgrade declaration and thus normalize relations between the two countries, discontinued since 1948.[15]

events.description: During the FIFA World Cup, police had to intervene multiple times in fights between Chilean and Italian players in one of the most violent games in football history.
events.html: • 1962 – During the FIFA World Cup, police had to intervene multiple times in fights between Chilean and Italian players in one of the most violent games in football history.

entities.name: Battle of Santiago (1962 FIFA World Cup)

events.description: The Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) is formed.
events.html: • 1964 – The Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) is formed.[16]

events.description: Surveyor program: Surveyor 1 lands in Oceanus Procellarum on the Moon, becoming the first U.S. spacecraft to soft-land on another world.
events.html: • 1966 – Surveyor program: Surveyor 1 lands in Oceanus Procellarum on the Moon, becoming the first U.S. spacecraft to soft-land on another world.

events.description: Luis Monge is executed in Colorado's gas chamber, in the last pre-Furman execution in the United States.
events.html: • 1967 – Luis Monge is executed in Colorado's gas chamber, in the last pre-Furman execution in the United States.

events.description: Protests in West Berlin against the arrival of the Shah of Iran are brutally suppressed, during which Benno Ohnesorg is killed by a police officer. His death results in the founding of the terrorist group Movement 2 June.
events.html: • 1967 – Protests in West Berlin against the arrival of the Shah of Iran are brutally suppressed, during which Benno Ohnesorg is killed by a police officer. His death results in the founding of the terrorist group Movement 2 June.

events.description: Pope John Paul II starts his first official visit to his native Poland, becoming the first Pope to visit a Communist country.
events.html: • 1979 – Pope John Paul II starts his first official visit to his native Poland, becoming the first Pope to visit a Communist country.

events.description: After an emergency landing because of an in-flight fire, twenty-three passengers aboard Air Canada Flight 797 are killed when a flashover occurs as the plane's doors open. Because of this incident, numerous new safety regulations are put in place.
events.html: • 1983 – After an emergency landing because of an in-flight fire, twenty-three passengers aboard Air Canada Flight 797 are killed when a flashover occurs as the plane's doors open. Because of this incident, numerous new safety regulations are put in place.

events.description: The Lower Ohio Valley tornado outbreak spawns 66 confirmed tornadoes in Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, and Ohio, killing 12.
events.html: • 1990 – The Lower Ohio Valley tornado outbreak spawns 66 confirmed tornadoes in Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky, and Ohio, killing 12.

entities.name: June 1990 Lower Ohio Valley tornado outbreak

events.description: In Denver, Timothy McVeigh is convicted on 15 counts of murder and conspiracy for his role in the 1995 bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City, in which 168 people died. He was executed four years later.
events.html: • 1997 – In Denver, Timothy McVeigh is convicted on 15 counts of murder and conspiracy for his role in the 1995 bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City, in which 168 people died. He was executed four years later.

events.description: Space Shuttle Discovery is launched on STS-91, the final mission of the Shuttle-Mir program.
events.html: • 1998 – Space Shuttle Discovery is launched on STS-91, the final mission of the Shuttle-Mir program.[17]

events.description: Europe launches its first voyage to another planet, Mars. The European Space Agency's Mars Express probe launches from the Baikonur space center in Kazakhstan.
events.html: • 2003 – Europe launches its first voyage to another planet, Mars. The European Space Agency's Mars Express probe launches from the Baikonur space center in Kazakhstan.

events.description: Former Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak is sentenced to life imprisonment for his role in the killing of demonstrators during the 2011 Egyptian revolution.
events.html: • 2012 – Former Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak is sentenced to life imprisonment for his role in the killing of demonstrators during the 2011 Egyptian revolution.

events.description: Telangana officially becomes the 29th state of India, formed from ten districts of northwestern Andhra Pradesh.
events.html: • 2014 – Telangana officially becomes the 29th state of India, formed from ten districts of northwestern Andhra Pradesh.

events.description: Following a request from Ankara, the United Nations officially changed the name of the Republic of Turkey in the organization from what was previously known as "Turkey" to "Türkiye."
events.html: • 2022 – Following a request from Ankara, the United Nations officially changed the name of the Republic of Turkey in the organization from what was previously known as "Turkey" to "Türkiye."[18]

events.description: A collision between two passenger trains and a parked freight train near the city of Balasor, Odisha in eastern India, results in 296 deaths and more than 1,200 people injured.
events.html: • 2023 – A collision between two passenger trains and a parked freight train near the city of Balasor, Odisha in eastern India, results in 296 deaths and more than 1,200 people injured.[19]
